<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920313-0039</DOCNO><DOCID>920313-0039.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing Brief -- Franklin Electronic Publishers Inc.:   New Mexico Approves Use   Of Firm's Electronic Books</HL><DATE>03/13/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE B2</SO><CO>   FPUB</CO><MS>TECHNOLOGY (TEC)</MS><IN>COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)</IN><RE>NEW JERSEY (NJ)NEW MEXICO (NM)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Franklin Electronic Publishers Inc. said the New MexicoBoard of Education has approved the use of its hand-heldelectronic reference books for use in the state's schools.   Franklin, of Mount Holly, N.J., said it is the first timea state has adopted electronic books as part of its textbookadoption process. A spokeswoman said, though, that it is tooearly to tell how many sales will result from New Mexico'sapproval.</LP><TEXT>   Franklin said its devices are already being used in some7,000 schools across the U.S., because some local schooldistricts have approved their use. A spokeswoman said themost popular devices are Franklin's speaking dictionaries,which pronounce the word that a student looks up and whichalso contain a thesaurus and a spelling checker.   Electronic books, initially a novelty, have started tocatch on largely because it can be much easier to have thecomputer search for a topic or string of words than to do itmanually. The books are expected to become more popular asimprovements in computer-chip technology increase the speedof the search and the memory capability of the books.</TEXT></DOC>